	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>March 20th 1866</date>.</p>
				<p>Dear Sir.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I received in due time your<lb/> kind lines of ...&#44; as also your issue<lb/> of this month&#44; in which I had the<lb/> pleasure of perusing the article<lb/> concerning the laying of the cor<lb/>nerstone of the Temple &#8220;Emanu&#45;el&#8221;<lb/> in <placeName>Cura&#231;ao</placeName>.  The reason why<lb/> I did not ere this acknowledge<lb/> the receipt of the former &#38; express<lb/> my thanks for its amiable con<lb/>tents is merely on account of<lb/> the manifold business I was<lb/> overcharged with of late&#44; but I<lb/> hope this delay will not pre<lb/>vent you from remaining  con<lb/>vinced that the friendly feelings<lb/> therein manifested towards me<lb/> and fully reciprocated.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With regard to the insert<lb/>ion of the above mentioned<lb/> article&#44; I must say that it<lb/> afforded me no little pleasure</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>as in my humble opinion you<lb/> have thereby given a signal<lb/> proof to the world&#44; that while<lb/> advocating your principles<lb/> on the broad ground of Juda<lb/>ism you do not allow your<lb/> self to be made the champion<lb/> of any private party&#44; which<lb/> while pretending to defend<lb/> religion do not aim but at<lb/> personalities. By the by let<lb/> me assure you that if you were<lb/> to become acquainted with<lb/> the two parties in <placeName>Cura&#231;ao</placeName> you<lb/> will soon find out that the<lb/> liberal one is by far not the<lb/> worst of the two.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Wishing to send my friends<lb/> there some copies of the said<lb/> number of the &#8220;Occident&#8221; you<lb/> will please remit me about<lb/> twenty five informing me at<lb/> the same time of their value.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Believe me  Dear Sir&#44; Yours Truly.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">A. J. Dovale</persName>.</p>
		</body>
